om/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/3500x1969+0+764/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F80%2F57%2Fd056e8c242d7842e3f25c9eeac40%2Flk-book-of-alchemy-gettyimages-2179506351-copy.jpg" class="img" alt="A photo collage showing a pair of hands in black-and-white holding an open journal. Handwritten cursive script is visible on the leaves of the open pages and three tissue paper flowers grow from the open book. Three butterflies hover around the flowers and an upright pencil hovers to the right of the open book. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Vertical photo collage of hand hold open book herbarium encyclopedia environment plant care butterfly isolated on painted background.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Deagreez; Pravokrugulnik; paladin13, Israel Sebastian/Getty Images; Collage by NPR &lt;br&gt;/iStockphoto                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Keeping a journal helped writer Suleika Jaouad navigate her battle with leukemia at 22, life after treatment and the pandemic. Now, she has released &lt;em&gt;The Book of Alchemy: A Creative Practice for an Inspired Life&lt;/em&gt;, which expands on her approach to journaling. It's a collection of essays and writing prompts from 100 writers and artists. Jaouad shares tips with &lt;em&gt;Life Kit &lt;/em&gt;on how to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/31/nx-s1-5464815/how-to-keep-a-daily-journal-book-of-alchemy" target="_blank"&gt;reignite your writing practice&lt;/a&gt; if you're feeling stuck, bored, or uninspired. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;✏️ Set a duration of time you plan to journal daily. Being consistent can help you form unexpected and interesting writing.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;✏️ Try adding journaling to a non-negotiable part of your routine, like when you sit down for your morning coffee.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;✏️ There is no right or wrong way to journal. You can use a phone app; don't let expectations like needing a pen and paper hinder your enjoyment.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;✏️ Try this prompt to get you started: Write a day in the life of your dreams a couple of years out. But do so in the present tense.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;For more guidance on how to start journaling, &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5464815:g-s1-80301" target="_blank"&gt;listen to this episode of NPR's &lt;em&gt;Life Kit&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. Subscribe to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/life-kit" target="_blank"&gt;the &lt;em&gt;Life Kit&lt;/em&gt; newsletter&lt;/a&gt; for expert advice on love, money, relationships and more.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Picture show&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-80906" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 7925;         --source-height: 4458;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7925x4458+0+825/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F84%2F20%2F90ce63704b3ebce8bb8573e90f59%2Fap24266381806727.jpg" class="img" alt="Divya Deshmukh of India during the final round of the 45th Chess Olympiad in Budapest, Hungary on Sept 22, 2024." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Divya Deshmukh of India during the final round of the 45th Chess Olympiad in Budapest, Hungary on Sept 22, 2024.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Denes Erdos/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;India is poised to take over the chess world, especially after 19-year-old Divya Deshmukh's recent victory at the FIDE Women's Chess World Cup. This achievement marks India's 88th grandmaster — a title awarded to the best players globally. Since the pandemic, chess has experienced a significant resurgence worldwide. With more leisure time, people began playing online and watching on YouTube. India has emerged as one of the biggest beneficiaries of this boom. Traditionally, Indian parents don't encourage their children to pursue sports seriously. But chess, which mirrors academic pursuits, has gained acceptance. Now, India is making sure its youth are poised to checkmate with a system created to teach "from the grassroots" of the sport, according to chess trainer Venkat Saravanan. Take a look at &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goats-and-soda/2025/08/05/g-s1-80632/whats-the-secret-to-indias-moves-to-conquer-the-global-chess-scene" target="_blank"&gt;how they are making strategic moves&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="res881200138" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5560;         --source-height: 3127;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s=1100&amp;c=50&amp;f=jpeg" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/06/20/gettyimages-1221108753_wide-5c5637a027f6fd169158b60515cb475cf768d420.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" class="img" alt="A statue commemorating Confederate Gen. Albert Pike sits on the ground moments after protesters toppled it late Friday night in Washington, D.C." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt;          &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A statue commemorating Confederate Gen. Albert Pike sits on the ground moments after protesters toppled it late Friday night in Washington, D.C.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Eric Baradat/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;The National Park Service &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/08/05/nx-s1-5493106/confederate-statue-albert-pike-reinstall" target="_blank"&gt;plans to restore and reinstall&lt;/a&gt; in Washington, D.C., a statue of Albert Pike, a Confederate general and Freemason leader. It was vandalized and taken down during the Black Lives Matter protests in June 2020.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;The U.S. Coast Guard issued a 300-page report yesterday stating the deaths of the passengers in the Titan submersible implosion two years ago &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/08/05/nx-s1-5493502/coast-guard-titan-submersible-oceangate-investigation" target="_blank"&gt;were preventable. It faulted OceanGate CEO&lt;/a&gt; Stockton Rush, who designed and piloted the vessel.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;On TikTok and Instagram, the word "clanker" as a catch-all term for robots and AI has reached viral levels. Context clues show the term is not a good thing. The Word of the Week series &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/08/06/nx-s1-5493360/clanker-robot-slur-star-wars" target="_blank"&gt;breaks down exactly what it means&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
